\begin_layout Section
Uncovered Interest Parity (UIP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the empirical evidence, the main factors affecting exchange
 rate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Future expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Interest rates differential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trade account (exports / imports) and trade policy can affect it as
 well, but mostly in the 
\series bold
long-term
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UIP is the leading theory for the 
\series bold
short-term
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic rationale is: suppose an investor wishes to transfer money form
 today to tomorrow.
 The question is, whether to do it with a Shekel or a Dollar denominated
 instrument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One option is to use a Shekel denominated instrument.
 An alternative is to convert the money to Dollar, invest it and then convert
 back.
 The UIP theory states that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[1+i(NIS)]=[1+i(\$)]\times\left[1+\frac{E_{t}[S_{t+1}-S_{t}]}{S_{t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume risk neutrality.
 Notice that in the first option, everything is known ahead and there is
 no risk.
 In the second option, as the position is uncovered, there is uncertainity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium condition for portfolio allocation, one should be indifferent
 between the 2 alternative (otherwise funds would move).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The UIP theory assumes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Free capital movement, no control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assets are perfect substitutes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Risk neutrality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A flexible exchange rate is essential, otherwise a black market would arise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A useful approximation is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i(NIS)=i(\$)+\left[\frac{E_{t}[S_{t+1}-S_{t}]}{S_{t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meaning, the domestic interest rate equals the sum of the foreign interest
 rate and the expected domestic depreciation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if the domestic interest rate is 1% and the foreign one is
 0.6%, the market expected a domestic depreciation of 0.4%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{t}=\frac{E_{t}[S_{t+1}]}{[1+i(NIS)-i(\$)]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spot exchange rate is equal to the expected furute exchange rate, divided
 by the interest rate spread.
 The expectations are 
\series bold
self-fulfilling 
\series default
- expected rates influence current ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rational expectations: in forming expectations, market use the same model
 that generates the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current exchange rate depends on the expected future path of the intereset
 rate differential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, when the FED announces something regarding the interest rate,
 it influences the exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Impossible Trinity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The policy trilemma: a nation cannot have free capital mobility, monetary
 independence and a fixed exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the mean time, we consider 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interest rate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as equal both to the CB rate and the assets return rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Covered Interest Parity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to use a 
\series bold
forward contract
\series default
 to fix the future delivery exchange rate.
 In such case the equation is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[1+i(\$)]=[1+i(\$)]\times\left[\frac{F_{t}}{S_{t}}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which eliminates the exchange rate uncertainity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation becomes an arbitrage condition and it must hold, because any
 deviation from it will be immeiately exploited.
 In fact, it is an 
\series bold
identity
\series default
.
 Banks publish spot rates together with forward rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From an investment perspective, thie equation is not interesting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uncovered interest parity is interesting for the investors, as they can
 take a speculative position accordng to their 
\series bold
beliefs
\series default
 regarding the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Carry Trades
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When an investor borrows the equivalent of the domestic currency in the
 foreign currency, invests and returns the loan, according to the equilibrium
 condition of the UIP, his expected gain should be 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Japanese Yen carry trades have been popular, as their interest rates are
 very low.
 In the last year it is also true for USD.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

base
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (funding) currency is the currency in which money is borrowed.
 If the interest rate of the domestic rate is high, it makes carry trade
 more attractive.
 The problem is that the future exchange rate is unknown, imposing a high
 risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Carry trade is considered a standard current strategy today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bank of Japan keeps pushing their rate downwards, which might have implicati
ons in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Between 2012 - 2016 both the housing prices index and the effective exchange
 rate of the GBP have been increasing.
 In theory, it provided a good profit opportunity - to gain both on the
 appreciating currency and on its interest rate.
 These expectatinos feeded each other, attracting more speculative investors
 and leads to a 
\series bold
bubble
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2016 a referendum on the Brexit was held in the U.K.
 Since then (and even before) the GBP effective exchange rate has fallen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Carry trades did extremely well (better than bonds and equities) in the
 1990s and reached their peak in 2013.
 Yet they tend to 
\series bold
underperform
\series default
 them in the last decade (starting in 2008), as there were many surprising
 evens in the global Economy.
 It is unclear, whether it is a cyclical or a structural move, but for now
 their advantage have evaporated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When capital comes in, there is more credit in the financial market, more
 liquidity and optimism.
 When it goes out, the opposite happens ans the risk would increase.
 Many of the crises in the emerging markets (Argentina, Brazil) are related
 to capital inflows / outflows - which can be caused both by fundamentals
 and by speculation.
\end_layout

